<!doctype html>

<head>
    <title>{{status}} - {{title}} | Extended Emojis</title>
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">

    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;
            font-size: 1.2rem;
            display: flex;
            flex-flow: row wrap;

            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;

            width: 100vw;
            height: 100vh;

            margin: 0; padding: 0;
            background-color: #181a1b;
            color: rgb(232, 230, 227);

            line-height: 1.4;
        }

        span {
            margin: 20px;
            border: 5px solid rgb(53, 57, 59);
            padding: 20px;
            background-color: lightcoral;
            color: black;

            max-width: 700px;
        }

        details {
            font-size: 0.95rem;
        }

        details summary {
            user-select: none;
            cursor: pointer;
            margin: 10px 0;
        }

        details code {
            font-size: small;
            word-wrap: break-word;
        }

    </style>

</head>

<body>

<span id="x">

    <h2>{{status}} - {{title}}</h2>
    {{#if message}}<b>{{message}}</b><br/>{{/if}}
    Here are some things you can try: <br/>
    <ul>
        <li>To access a normal emoji, put it at the end of the base URL. For example, <a href="https://{{host}}/ðŸ˜Ž">https://{{host}}/ðŸ˜Ž</a></li>
        <li>To access a special emoji, go to /s/[emoji-id]/. For example, <a href="https://{{host}}/s/jeans">https://{{host}}/s/jeans</a>. </li>
        <li><a href="https://forms.gle/LYawk4LvAkC1ziKa9">Click here to add your own special emoji!</a></li>
    </ul>

    {{#if diagnostics}}
        <details>
            <summary>Click for diagnostic information</summary>
            <code>{{diagnostics}}</code>
        </details>
    {{/if}}


</span>

</body>

</html>